repugnarunt cum haec recusarent et palam dicerent Repuynarunt cum dicerent is a very usual construction, ‘ they resisted, saying ' : commentators have found greater difficulty in explaining cum haec recusarent et dicerent. We might translate ‘they resisted, protestin9 aqainst these proposals and saying': but haec is not quite clear, and the phrase is suspicious occurring as it does immediately after recusando, used absolutely. Madvig (followed by Miiller) makes the simple change to reputarent, on which reading Ilaec anticipates se potuisse, etc. Dr. Reid proposes refutarent: haec would then: ‘arguments such as Accius has used.' It is simplest to adhere to the text, and to explain recusare of ‘raising a legal plea,’ as in ἓ 156 : cp. ἓ 154 non hoc recusabant ne, etc.
